<br>
&quot;A man who brings a handgun to a gun fight is a fool&quot;. Can't remember who said that, but the principle is sound. Long barrels are much more accurate at much further distances. The longer the barrel, the more stable the flight of the bullet becomes. Handguns were designed for portability and are best for targets within 50ft (30ft or under is optimal).<br>
<br>
Hitting a stationary target at 10ft (ie a person firing a weapon at you) when you are scared can be alot harder than you think. Police officers have been known to fire several rounds at this close of a range and still miss due to adrenaline. Firing a weapon in self defense at a live target in the heat of the moment is alot different than shooting on the firing range. That is why you have to practice responding to those situations until it becomes instinct, taking the thought process out of it.<br>
<br>
One thing I haven't seen mentioned in this thread is ammo. The round you are firing is just as important as the weapon itself. If you think you are going to fire a FMJ round and your target is just going to fall to the ground when hit, you are most likely in for a big surprise. FMJs transfer little energy and energy transfer is the key to stopping a target. That means you have to use a hollow point ammunition which shortens your range even more.<br>
<br>
Anyway, there is a huge difference between firing to defend your life and practicing on the firing range... huge difference.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
